04347nam a22005775i 9780774855570DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072007xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748555707 a10.1515/97807748555702doi  a(DE-B1597)661279  a(OCoLC)1320996175  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJZ1318.B7813 2007eb 7aPOL0330002bisacsh04a327.1011 aBrunelle, Dorval, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom World Order to Global Disorder :bStates, Markets, and Dissent /cDorval Brunelle. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tBuilding the Postwar Order -- tWelfare States and Social Rights -- tInternationalism versus Regionalism in the Cold War -- tCanada and the Cold War: The Shift to Regionalism -- tCanada-US Free Trade: From the Regional to the Global -- tFeatures of a Global Order -- tConsultation or Contention: Social Movements and Globalization -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnti-globalization activism world-wide attests to the tensions between globalization and civil society. To better understand this fraught relationship, Dorval Brunelle compares two social orders separated by a half-century. The post-World War II order entailed a broad vision uniting three complementary objectives � security, justice, and welfare � which were entrusted to a network of international and national institutions. In contrast, globalization, with wealth as its only objective, is undermining and overhauling the values and institutions of the previous order, including the United Nations and the welfare state. From World Order to Global Disorder demonstrates the profound effect of globalization on relations between the state, civil society, and markets, as well as on collective and individual rights. As neo-liberalism evolves into globalization, governments are eschewing their role as public guardians and are instead bartering the very assets and resources their citizens' labour and activism created and preserved. However, no constitution makes governments owners of collective assets: governments are merely trustees. In this context, the world's citizens have a tremendous task before them: in the wake of the welfare state, their social forums are indispensable in the quest for a more just and equitable world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGlobalization. 0aInternational economic relations. 0aRegionalism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Globalization.2bisacsh1 aHoward, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077485557040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774855570423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774855570/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles